Whereas water is an essential, irreplaceable component to all sectors of society from agriculture,
			 manufacturing, and energy development to domestic consumption, recreation,
			 human health, and ecological maintenance;

Whereas the practice of managing multiple water consumption interests is made more challenging by
			 the compounding effects of climate change, water pollution, and
			 population;

Whereas groundwater resources, vital to community water systems and irrigation throughout the
			 United States, are rapidly being depleted due to increased demands coupled
			 with changes in hydrologic and climate patterns;

Whereas chronic water shortages are increasingly felt throughout the United States with millions of
			 people living in drought conditions and millions more indirectly affected
			 by drought, such as through increased food prices;
